                  </did>
                  <altformavail>
                     <p>Facsimile, showing the last seven lines and the note, on page six of
								the MS Instructions, the upper three-fourths of which are reproduced, in
								<bibref title="http://www.thomasgray.org/resources/biblb.shtml#SmM_1989"
                                linktype="simple"> Smith (ed.), <title render="italic" linktype="simple">Index</title> (1989), no. 5, following p.
								xvii</bibref>, where it is described
							</p>
                  </altformavail>
                  <bibliography>
                     <bibref title="http://www.thomasgray.org/resources/biblb.shtml#SmM_1989"
                             linktype="simple">Smith (ed.), <title render="italic" linktype="simple">Index</title> (1989), item GrT 51, 	84</bibref>
                     <bibref title="" linktype="simple">Heist, Michael, "RE: Modern (Bound) Manuscripts,
								vol.52, Robert H. Taylor Collection". E-mail to the editor, 11
								January 2007</bibref>
                  </bibliography>
                  <scopecontent>
                     <p>Autograph fair copy, untitled but numbered 7. and identified from the
								table of contents as "7. The Fatal Sisters (from the
								Norse-tongue)", and headed
								"From the Orcades of Thormodus Torfaeus. Hafniae. 1697. Fol: Vitt
								er orpit Fyrir valfalli &amp;c:", preceded by a "Prefix",
								followed by a note on the Valkyriur, and, elsewhere in the MS (p. 9) an
								advertisement and two notes, in MS Instructions to
								<extref href="http://www.thomasgray.org/resources/glnames.shtml#Beattie, James, 1735-1803"
                                show="replace"
                                linktype="simple">
                           <persname normal="Beattie, James, 1735-1803">Beattie</persname>
                        </extref> for the <extref href="http://www.thomasgray.org/cgi-bin/view.cgi?collection=primary&amp;edition=1768a&amp;text=fsio"
                                show="replace"
                                linktype="simple">
                           <date normal="1768" type="publication" era="ce" calendar="gregorian">1768</date>
                           <geogname normal="Glasgow (Glasgow, Scotland, United Kingdom), inhabited place          [7017283]">Glasgow</geogname> edition</extref>, originally sent in a <extref href="http://www.thomasgray.org/cgi-bin/display.cgi?text=tgal0522"
                                show="replace"
                                linktype="simple">letter</extref>, <date normal="17680201" era="ce" calendar="gregorian">1 February 1768</date>.</p>
                  </scopecontent>
                  <separatedmaterial>
                     <p>The <extref href="http://www.thomasgray.org/cgi-bin/display.cgi?text=tgal0522"
                                show="replace"
                                linktype="simple">letter</extref> in which these instructions were originally
								sent is now at Historic Collections, King's College, University
								of Aberdeen, <geogname normal="Aberdeen (Aberdeen, Scotland, United Kingdom), inhabited place          [7009782]">Aberdeen</geogname>, UK.</p>
                  </separatedmaterial>
